      "contentSections": [
        {
          "type": "tier-comparison",
          "title": "Which Program Fits Your Parent's Income?",
          "content": [
            {
              "tier": "QMB (Qualified Medicare Beneficiary)",
              "income": "Individual: $1,350/month | Couple: $1,824/month",
              "benefits": "Pays Part A premiums (if any), Part B premiums, deductibles, coinsurance, and copayments. Protects against balance billing.",
              "note": "Most comprehensive coverage"
            },
            {
              "tier": "SLMB (Specified Low-Income Medicare Beneficiary)",
              "income": "Individual: $1,616/month | Couple: $2,184/month",
              "benefits": "Pays Medicare Part B premiums only ($174.70/month in 2026).",
              "note": "Must have Medicare Part B to qualify"
            },
            {
              "tier": "QI (Qualifying Individual)",
              "income": "Individual: $1,816/month | Couple: $2,455/month",
              "benefits": "Pays Medicare Part B premiums. Automatically qualifies for Extra Help with prescription costs.",
              "note": "Annual reapplication required, first-come first-served"
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one apply for multiple Medicare Savings Programs at once?",
          "answer": "No, your loved one will be enrolled in the highest program they qualify for based on income. If they qualify for QMB (lowest income limit), they'll get QMB benefits which cover the most costs."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's income is slightly over the limit?",
          "answer": "Louisiana may allow slightly higher income than the federal limits shown. Contact your local Medicaid office to verify current limits, as states can set limits up to slightly above federal standards."
        },
        {
          "question": "Will this affect my loved one's Medicare benefits or doctors?",
          "answer": "No, these programs work alongside Medicare, not instead of it. Your loved one keeps the same Medicare coverage, doctors, and benefits while the state pays their share of costs."
        },
        {
          "question": "Why does QI require reapplication every year when QMB and SLMB don't?",
          "answer": "QI has federal funding caps, so states must limit enrollment. Louisiana awards QI spots first-come, first-served each year, giving priority to people who had it the previous year but requiring everyone to reapply."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my loved one have both Medicare Savings Programs and full Medicaid?",
          "answer": "No, people receiving full Medicaid are not eligible for these programs. However, those with Medicare Savings Programs may qualify for limited Medicaid benefits in some situations."
        },
        {
          "question": "What does 'balance billing protection' mean for QMB recipients?",
          "answer": "Healthcare providers cannot charge your loved one anything beyond what Medicare and QMB pay for covered services. If a provider tries to bill your loved one directly for Medicare-covered care, they're violating federal law."
        },
        {
          "question": "How much could my loved one save with these programs?",
          "answer": "At minimum, SLMB and QI save $2,096/year in Part B premiums. QMB recipients save much more since it also covers deductibles and copays, potentially $3,000-5,000+ annually depending on healthcare use."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply on behalf of my elderly loved one?",
          "answer": "Yes, family members can apply on behalf of aging loved ones. You'll need to provide documentation showing you're authorized to act on their behalf, such as power of attorney or representative payee status."
        }
      ],
