      "applicationNotes": [
        "You must be capable of self-direction even if you choose to work with an agency, this means you're responsible for hiring, firing, and supervising your care providers",
        "Annual re-evaluation is required to maintain services",
        "This program focuses on employability and avoiding institutionalization, not general aging-in-place support"
      ],
      "relatedPrograms": [
        "LT-PCS Medicaid (Long-Term Personal Care Services)",
        "Louisiana Medicaid",
        "Adult Day Care Services",
        "Community Choices Waiver"
      ],
      "contentSections": [],
      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can a family member apply for SPAS on behalf of their disabled adult child?",
          "answer": "Yes, if you are the legal representative for someone who cannot self-direct their care. However, the program requires that either the participant or their legal representative be capable of hiring, firing, and supervising care providers. You'll need legal documentation proving your authority to act on their behalf."
        },
        {
          "question": "What's the difference between SPAS and LT-PCS Medicaid?",
          "answer": "SPAS has no specific income or asset limits but requires proof of unique economic need, while LT-PCS Medicaid has strict limits ($994/month income, $2,000 assets for singles in 2026). SPAS focuses on employability and disability services for adults 18+, while LT-PCS primarily serves elderly individuals 65+ or disabled individuals 21+."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I choose an agency to provide care instead of hiring individual providers?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can work with an agency, but you're still responsible for the self-direction requirements. This means you must be involved in hiring, firing, and supervising decisions even when working through an agency. The agency cannot make these decisions independently."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my income changes after I'm approved for SPAS?",
          "answer": "You must report income changes and participate in annual re-evaluation to maintain services. Since the program requires proof of unique economic need rather than meeting specific income limits, changes will be assessed to determine if you still qualify for the economic assistance."
        },
        {
          "question": "How specific does the physician verification need to be?",
          "answer": "Your treating physician must verify that you have significant disabilities and need the specific goods or services to prevent institutional placement or maintain employability. The verification should be detailed enough to support your application during the team evaluation process."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for SPAS and Medicaid at the same time?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can apply for both programs simultaneously since they have different eligibility criteria and serve different purposes. SPAS focuses on disability services and employability, while Medicaid provides broader healthcare coverage. Having one doesn't disqualify you from the other."
        }
      ],
