        {
          "question": "Can my loved one keep their house if it's worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes. The primary home is exempt from the $2,000 asset limit as long as your loved one lives there or intends to return. The home equity limit is $752,000 in 2026 (home value minus mortgage). The $2,000 limit applies to countable assets like bank accounts and investments."
        },
        {
          "question": "What exactly does 'Nursing Facility Level of Care' mean?",
          "answer": "This means your loved one needs daily help with activities like bathing, dressing, transferring, eating, or toileting, or has unstable medical conditions or cognitive issues requiring supervision. The determination is made through an interRAI Home Care Assessment, not just a doctor's opinion."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply for this program and regular Medicaid at the same time?",
          "answer": "You must apply for Medicaid Long-Term Care first through Healthy Louisiana at bayouhealth.com or 1-888-342-6207. Only after Medicaid approval can you request Community Choices Waiver services through your Regional Coordinating Council."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my loved one's care needs change after enrollment?",
          "answer": "Care plans can be modified through your Regional Coordinating Council and Supports for Caregivers provider. If needs increase significantly or decrease, reassessment may be required to adjust services and caregiver payment arrangements."
        },
        {
          "question": "Are there restrictions on which family members can be paid caregivers?",
          "answer": "Yes. Caregivers must be at least 18 years old, live with the care recipient, and be able to provide the required care. Spouses may have restrictions. The Supports for Caregivers provider will review eligibility during the enrollment process."
        }
